ATC.bioPage1:
Comprised of talents covering the corners of the world, ATC (A Touch of Class) turned a friendship into a global experience. Their single breakout "Around The World (La La La La La)" has sent ATC to the top of international charts as well as making them award winners and multple-award nominations. ATC debuted on Republic/Universal Records, arriving in the US on February 6, 2001 utilizing their dynamic, upbeat dance grooves, enticing ballads and sexy vocals that give their music a common appeal among fans around the world.

Based in Hamburg, Germany, ATC is compromised of early twenty-somethings Joe (New Zealand), Sarah (Australia), Tracey (England), and Livio (Northern Italy) who met as cast members in the German production of "Cats". While proving their dance skills in "Cats", it was the foursome's vocal crafts honed since childhood that propelled them into a best-selling act. As Joe recalls, "We really wanted to show the strenght of our voices and not just our dancing. We all had the same pop dreams. We're all just as strong as singers as we are dancers. In our live performances we have a massive dance show, but it's the songs that show all our talents."

Robert Miles.bioPage1:
Born Roberto Concina, son of an Italian military family stationed in Switzerland at the time. He lived in Switzerland until the age of 10 before moving to his homeland, the town of Fagagna, Italy.

Robert grew up listening to American Soul in the 1970's and began his musical career playing the piano as a child. At the age of 13, he began DJ'ing local house parties. By the late-'80s he was a regular in several hard trance clubs around Venice, going by the name Robert Milani. Eventually he changed his name to Miles as a symbol of the musical journey ahead of him.

He began producing his own music in the early-'90s. He worked on a basic studio system consisting of a sampler, mixer, keyboard and 32-track digital board. He began working on his first single, "Children" which was inspired by photos taken by his father while station in war-torn Yugoslavia. He produced this first anthem for only 150. The single slowly trickled onto the charts in German, France, Holland and Belgium before it became the biggest single on the European charts in 1996.

Safri Duo.bioPage1:
Morten Friis and Uffe Savery studied at the Royal Danish Conservatory of Classical Music. While both classically trained, their studies turned to percussive instruments. Since 1994, they've played a wide range of percussive instruments with a focus on marimbas and vibes. As a result, the "duo" produced several classical albums such as "Goldrush" and "Bach To The Future" up until 1998.

The following year, Universal Denmark's classical department discovered the two musicians and teamed them with trance producer Michael Parsberg. Having signed with a danish record label, the duo began work to produce an album merging dance, trance and pop with ethnic percussive sounds.

"Played Alive", the team's best known single work, landed a Danish Grammy Award for "Best Club Hit 2000" while topping the European club charts. This and other singles gained support from worldwide artists the likes of DJ Tandu and Airscape.

Their latest album, "Episode II" was released on May 28, 2001. It features their trademark percussive sound blended with smooth electronica, transporting listeners to new aural worlds.

Paul Van Dyk.bioPage1:
Hailed as the "Messiah of Trance", Paul Van Dyk is among the forefathers of the trance revolution. His is an understanding of the movements of human imagination, emotion and energy. "I don't want to lead people", he says, "I want to tempt them, to create a new world for them, just for that very small moment when they are losing themselves in my music. I want to inspire them." Simply put, Paul Van Dyk creates music that folds around the soul of the listener and captures their emotions.

Born December 16th, 1971 in Eisenhuettenstadt, East Germany, Paul grew up in communist East Berlin. Prior to Germanys reunification, he at least had an early window to the capitalist world via the cross-border airwaves. His early influences came from listening to the radio show of Monika Dietl. "I was really captivated by the music of 'The Smiths' and 'New Order'. It (the music) was very strong and emotional." Soon after, Paul began his experiments with a basic turntable setup. Moving to Berlin in the late 80's, he began to line up gigs around the city.

By 1991, Paul began making original compositions. Teaming up with mentor and friend, Cosmic Baby, under the name "Visions of Shiva", he
Paul Van Dyk.bioPage2:
released his first track "Perfect Day" in 1992. The following year, he released the club hit of the year with a remix of "Love Stimulation" by Humate. He later released his first album, "45 RPM" and began regularly spinning sets at the legendary "E-Werk" club. He continued gaining respect through his remixes of many renowned artists including New Order, a source of his original inspiration. FInally, the release of "Seven Ways", his second album, firmly established Paul Van Dyk as one of the world's great electronic artists. The release of "Seven Ways" propelled Van Dyk and singles including "Beautiful Place", "Forbidden Fruit" and "Words" to the top of British and European dance charts. Continuing to spin until Berlin's "E-Werk" club closed, he worked along side fellow superstar DJ's such as Nick Warren, BT, Dave Seaman and Sasha.

Not to be sheltered by success in the studio, Paul's talent is also recognized as a world renowned DJ. "As I began my career as a DJ I discovered that there is a really deep communication between DJ and people. I learned how to move the crowd and how to create atmosphere", he remembers. He served a residency at "Twilo" in New York and at
Paul Van Dyk.bioPage3:
the acclaimed "Gatecrasher" in Sheffield as well as his hometown of Berlin. He continues to regularly create that experience.

"I've never made music for being trendy or making the fat money. I make music for myself... it comes directly from my stomach. My music springs from an intense feeling. And every track has its own little story..." In the end, it is about the experience.

ATB.bioPage1:
DJ Andre Tanneberger was born in Germany in 1973. Inspired to bring his own sounds to the trance community, he scored his first European club hit with 1999's release of "9 PM (Till I Come)". It rocketed him into the European spotlight and gained him international recognition as the hot single was played in clubs the world over. Later that year brought the release of his full-length album "Movin' Melodies".

For his second full-length release, Tanneberger collaborated with Heather Nova, Enigma and the Canadian rock band, Wild Strawberries. The double-disc release in 2000 was filled with dance floor tunes and down tempo melodies. In mid-2000, ATB released "Killer", a remake of a Seak and Adamski track. It featured Drew Williams on vocals. That fall ATB had his third album release of "Two Worlds".

Ayla.bioPage1:
Ingo Kunzi, alias DJ Tandu was born on November 7th 1966 in Stuttgart, Germany. He began producing music in 1984. In 1995 He started a new music project called Ayla. The name comes from a girl present in the studio at the time he recorded the first single, which he also named Ayla. The single was released in the beginning of 1996 and it immediately became a success. People never seem to stop making remixes of this single either. Kosmonova, Taucher and Veracocha have made several remixes of Ayla, and now, even Tandu himself, has made one. The second single under his new project(Ayla), was released a year later in 1997. It was called Atlantis. Unfortunately, for some reason, as this is a wonderful aural melody, it didn't gain much momentum.

Tandu joined forces with Taucher and Torsten Stenzel in March 1998. They released a single called Ayla Part II and this time the success was even bigger than with the first single. Six months later He began producing the Ayla project on his own again and released Liebe, a single which is a conversion of an old favorite with the same name released by Cosmic Baby, who's music as well can be found here in the recesses of Massinova. It was, once

Cosmic Baby.bioPage1:
Harald Bluechel was born on February 19, 1966 in Nuremberg, Germany. A classically trained concert pianist who began at the Nuremberg Conservatory at the tender age of 7, he has been composing pieces for synthesizer since discovering Tangerine Dream and Kraftwerk in 1980. In 1987, continuing his musical studies, Cosmic Baby moved to Berlin and entered the Art Academy, composing experimental music on a Fairlight computer. By the age of 14, Cosmic Baby had composed his first synthesizer peice. At the Technical University, he studied sound engineering, learning the technical side of music production. In 1988, he met the major players of the Berlin scene: Tanith, WestBam, & Kid Paul. Teaming up with Paul Van Dyk, Bluechel hit the top of the British charts with "Perfect Day" under the Visions of Shiva alias.

Bluechel's music reflects a melding of his classical training and the influences of electronic music, his melodic trance style evidence of his in-born talent. Bluechel, speaking about his music, says, "When it becomes difficult, in face of the flood without comment, but very well filtered information and formatted thought patterns are there for you to concentrate and to

Max Graham.bioPage1:
Having traveled since he was born in 1971, Max Graham, living in London, Spain, Los Angeles and New York before settling in Ottawa, speaks through his music as an attentive and insightful observer. He started spinning in 1986, when He first touched a pair of turntables at the tender age of fifteen. Over the fourteen years of his career, Max has dabbled in many kinds of dance music. Originally a scratch DJ, He met house music in the early nineties, at the beginning of what would become a renaissance period for dance music across the globe.

In these landmark years between 1992 and 1995 the music world would witness the birth of progressive house, and with it such artists as BT and Underworld, and such DJs as Sasha and Paul Oakenfold to push the envelope to even futher reaches into trance and beyond. Max was one of the first DJs in Canada to pick up on this distinctive sound, and he went to work interpreting it for himself.

Of his three releases to date, Backdraft and Airtight have gone one and two on the Balance chart, with Airtight making an impact in the UK with a top ten on the Buzz Chart, top three on Cool Cuts, airtime on Pete Tong's Essential Mix on Radio One, and
Max Graham.bioPage2: licensing offers from such compilations as Oakenfold's latest release Another World, a must-buy album. Max has completed remixes for Virgin, Platipus and Nettwerk, and is constantly building his own studio so he can continue to produce and release his own work.

Art of Trance.bioPage1:
Simon Berry has had a long and involved career in the electronica music industry. Having first followed his passion at the age of 18, Berry moved to London where he could immerse himself in the music that he loved. Like most of the late-'90s producers, Berry found his love for electronica after hearing the techno tracks from the late-'80s of Chicago and Detroit. Hitting the clubs, such as Troll and Chemistry, he became enamored by the proto-trance classic "Acperience". He then set off on hisjourney to create his own sound.

His first release on his Platipus label, "Deeper Than Deep" caught the attention of Carl Cox who agreed to a remix of the track in 1995. Berry quickly climbed the charts. Collaborating with future Terra Ferma producer Claudio Guisanni as Union Jack, resulting in "Two Full Moons and a Trout". The following year saw Berry's full-length album on Platipus, "Wildlife on One". It is known asa cornerstone album and among the first to feature the proto-trance sound growing in Germany and the U.K.

During his work on his second release in 1997, his studio was burglarized. Although a major setback, he moved on. In late 1998 he released his biggesthit single yet,

Orbital.bioPage1:
Phil and Paul Hartnoll formed Orbital in 1987, in Sevenoaks, Kent, England. Older brother Phil (b. Jan 9, 1964) was working as a bricklayer, Paul (b. May 19, 1968) was playing with local band Noddy and the Satellites. Their first track, Chime, was recorded in '87, but wasn't released as a single until '89. At this time they made their live debut, in a pub the Grasshopper, Westerham, Kent. The following year, Chime was re-released reaching 17 in the British chart. At this time the Orbital name was taken from the M25, London's orbital motorway, otherwise known by ravers at the time as the magic roundabout.

The second single Omen never made the Top 40, but the subsequent Satan reached number 31. In September '91 the untitled first album (the "green" album) was released, from which a fourth single, Midnight was later taken. EPs Mutations and Radiccio followed in '92. The "green" second album, another untitled work, which includes Massinova's chart topping song, Halcyon+On+On, was released in '93. This was more of a complete work than the "brown" album, which was more a collection of unrelated tracks. EPs, The Peel Session and Diversions (US only) followed.

At the '94 Glastonbury
Orbital.bioPage2:
Festival, Orbital received rave reviews for their headlining set, which was performed in darkness, both of them wearing head-torches, lurking behind the banks. Their live sets made no use of DAT tapes, a mainstay of many electronic acts, which allowed them more spontaneity, and proved that dance music could be exciting to watch live.

Snivilization became the first named album in '94, reaching number 4 in the UK Album chart. The Box, a 28 minute 'orchestral' single preceded the album In Sides in '96. Three years later in '99 The Middle of Nowhere is the most recent album from the Hartnolls.

The Altogether is to be released later this year (2001).

BT.bioPage1:
Few producers have been as instrumental in shaping the sound of electronica as Brian Transeau. Successfully weaving electronica genres with his classical training, BT stands out among electronica artists as a pioneer. Having transformed the British dance community in the mid-'90s, he paved the way for other dance and dream-house producers such as Robert Miles, Sash! and BBE.

Transeau grew up in a musical playground having started playing the piano at the age of two. His classical training began while only thirteen years old. Born and raised in Washington, D.C. Transeau listened to Depeche Mode and Yes even while studying string arrangement and orchestration. He attended Berklee School of Music in Boston for one year before dropping out.

After a brief stint in L.A., he return to his home turf where he joined longtime friend Ali Shirazinia's new Deep Dish production. While there he lended his talents to the synthesizer for albums by Salt-N-Pepa and Tyler Collins. In 1993, his time came with the debut of two singles "A Moment of Truth" and "Relativity" both of which gained immense popularity in Britain.

Sonic Theory.bioPage1:
Starting as "Acid Revolution", the Sonic Theory has made incredible leaps since their humble beginnings back in 1996. Originally started by a group of DJ's, the group now features the collective aural experience of Bones and Dingus (a.k.a. DJ Hiest and DJ Orion, respectively). The group has begun to gain recognition globably via MTV Undiscovered in Europe and the real.com network.

Through the use of a variety of synthesizers such as the Yamaha CS2x, Alesis QS6, Roland JP-8080, and drum machines like the Roland MC-303 the group creates "an musical journey crafted to enrich your mind".

Delerium.bioPage1:
Witness the split music personalities of Vancouver duo Bill Leeb and Rhys Fulber. Better known for their work as the industrial-edged group Front Line Assembly, the Duo's decade-old alter ego, Delerium, fashions itself more on the lines of ambient worldbeat. Curiosity seekers who thrive on the beats of Enigma and Deep Forest would be well served to give the group's latest release, Reflections 2, a worthy listen.

Considering Leeb and Fulber's fondness for sampling, it may be surprising that the duo took the time and effort to record a real live choir. "Nowadays, the whole sample clearance issue has become ridiculous," says Leeb. "Record companies ask for outrageous amounts of money for Gregorian samples. It's still cheaper to pay a choir, rent a church, drag the equipment down there, transcribe the words to Latin and record it. It comes out to be half the price of clearing a 12-second sample, which I find totally bizarre." Leeb's vision of an outlet for musical ideas that didn't fit his alter-ego "Frontline Assembly" project has proven to be surprisingly successful, encompassing a broader scope. Delerium, with their more recent releases, showcase worldbeat, folk, pop, dance,

Chicane.bioPage1:
Chicane delivers a provocative dose of electronic music that blends Dream-House, ambient, trance, and a healthy dose of drum 'n' bass. Born Nick Bracegirdle, Chicane was a design student who performed under the name Disco Citizen with Leo Elstob.

Their first release out in 1995 on Deconstruction Records was a top 40 U.K. hit. Despite the success, the duo was unhappy with the label and departed to start Moderna Records and Cyanide Music. October 1998 Nick teams up with Ray "Madman" Hedges. The man who created hits for groups like Boyzone and B*Witched.

Together they wrote the largely popular single "Strong In Love".

The chemistry between the two seems to improve with 1999's release of the brilliantly chilled 'gaelic house' track "Saltwater". Nick wrote the song together with Ray Hedges again! It includes a sample from Clannad's "Theme From Harry's Game". Well not quite a sample actually. Nick invited Maire Brennan to the studio to re-record the vocals. The video was shot on a beach, and at the World reknown GATECRASHER in Sheffield. Chicane fans hoped for a UK top 10 hit. And they got it! It smashed in as #6 in the

Paul Oakenfold.bioPage2:
With Fung and another friend named Ian St. Paul, Oakenfold was introduced to the exploding club-scene on the vacation island of Ibiza (near the coast of Spain) during 1987 and imported the crucial mix of house, soul, Italian disco and alternative music later dubbed the Balearic style.

During 1988-89, house music and the Balearic style gestated at several Oakenfold-run club nights (Future at the Sound Shaft, then Spectrum and Land of Oz at Heaven) before emerging above terra firma as a distinctly British entity. Oakenfold and Steve Osborne had been working with new dance converts Happy Mondays, and their production for the 1989 Happy Mondays' single "(W.F.L.) Wrote for Luck" was voted Dance Record of the Year by the NME. The duo's production for the Happy Mondays' break-out full-length Pills 'n' Thrills 'n' Bellyaches placed them squarely in the vaunted territory of other new dance producers like Andrew Weatherall (who achieved similar success with Primal Scream's Screamadelica from the same year). Soon, major labels were lining up to have Oakenfold and Osborne remix their biggest pop stars including U2, Simply Red, New Order, the Cure, Massive Attack, M People, Arrested

Antiloop.bioPage1:
Antiloop features the talent of David Westerlund and Robin Soderman. Friends since childhood, being neighbors on Lindingo (an island in Stockholm), the pair began their musical trip together by vibing on a whole range of musical influences.

Classically trained, David is the musical brain of Antiloop and is clearly the genial type, keeping things in order although he's not always aware of it: "I'm incredibly absent minded and, I guess, bohemian", says David. "I sleep really long hours and I'm never on time for anything other than the studio. I prefer to work at night, so a lot of time I end up trying to get some sleep with the mixer table as a pillow".

Robin is Antiloop's producer and is, as David says, "a fabulous sound technician who makes the perfect mix". As well as continuing to build their name as both the act, Antiloop, and as a production unit in itself, the partners spend a log of time as DJ's in Stockholm, at one point hosting a leading night in the capital, "The Rebels Room", also the name of their studio.

Antiloop was formed in 1994 and released their first EP in 1995, "NSFMC" (Not Suitable For Mass Consumption). Having previously released 2 albums, their

Astral Projection.bioPage1:
Nissim and Perlmutter both began as dance/industrial DJs in Israel in the late-'80s. They released "Monster Mania", (recorded as SFX) in 1990, which was a big club hit. The duo ran an x-rave in New York for a while before returning to produce in Israel. In 1994, the group started a label named Outmosphere, which was renamed Trust in Trance in 1995. This label began in order to feature compilations. They released their first album of an ongoing series (Trust in Trance: Psychedelic Vibes) which featured the first of their own productions under the name Astral Projection. The second and third compilation albums gained popularity in Israel and Europe.

They released their first true Astral Projection album in 1997, "Dancing Galaxy" which became one of the best selling trance albums in history. They have since released two more Astral Projection albums and re-released some of their early SFX recordings.

Anjunabeats.bioPage1:
Anjunabeats Records was established in the summer of 1999 by Jono Grant and Paavo Siljamki. The "Anjuna Boys" met at the university having already begun to make a name for themselves independently as record producers. Two heads seemed better than one, so they decided to team up and establish a label for releasing their uplifting and progressive trance music.

Opening up with Anjunabeats "Volume 1", the bomb had been dropped. The label made off to a good start with support from DJs such as Pete Tong, Paul Oakenfold and Paul Van Dyk. A club hit in its own right, Anjunabeats "Volume 1" went on to secure the boys remix work for high profile acts.

Teaming up with fellow producer Tony McGuinness to form Above & Beyond, following their remix work on his own record, Nitromethane "Time To Die", they clicked and went on to remix Chakra "Home" for WEA. This was the lead mix and hit the number 1 spot in the UK club chart, causing big reactions on the nation's dancefloors. As a result, the remix requests rolled in. Above & Beyond have since produced remixes for artists Adamski, Dario G, Armin, Aurora and most recently Madonna. Madonna liked the Above & Beyond mix of "What it Feels like

Adamski.bioPage1:
Adamski's first recordings were cut at the age of 11 as a member of the Stupid Babies, a pre-teen punk duo (with his brother) immortalized on the Fast Products Earcom 3 sampler. He was also a member of Diskord Datkord in 1987, who released one single - a cover version of X-Ray Spex's "Identity" (his brother subsequently formed Garden Of Eden).

Adamski went on to record as a keyboard player on instrumental dance music records. His solo breakthrough came with the release of "N-R-G", which reached number 12 in the UK charts in January 1990. Unfortunately, legal action from Lucozade, who claimed the single plagiarized their advertising slogan, forced him to donate 5,000 of his royalties to charity. He replied with April's massive dancefloor hit and UK number 1, "Killer". This tautly orchestrated electronic piece was enhanced by the emotive vocals of guest vocalist Seal . September's follow-up, "The Space Jungle", which derived from "All Shook Up", was hammered by the critics, but still reached UK number 7.

While his former vocalist went on to national adoration, Adamski slipped from view, although he did enjoy a minor hit with "Flashback Jack" at the end of 1990. An epitaph, of

303 Infinity.bioPage1:
In May of 1996, Mikel Fair aka 303infinity began producing his acclaimed emotionally uplifting melodies. After joining onto the mp3.com bandwagon, Mikels music began reaching new ears and gained enormous popularity throughout the online community. What once began as an individual musical expedition from Houston, Texas became a world wide web phenomenon.

Since initially joining mp3.com, 303infinity has continuously remained popular among the community. They consistently remain at the top of the charts with new trance melodies expressing Mikel and Ninjas technical skill and artistic vision.

Aqua.bioPage1:
It took years of slow development and a series of steps for Aqua to make known it's fun and furious dance beats. It began back in 1989 with Claus Norreen and Soren Rasted working together to compose music for a Danish movie soundtrack. Rene McLean, at the time, was working as a DJ in Norway when he soon discovered Lene Grawford Nystrom singing on a TV show. In a meeting in Denmark, Rene introduced Lene to Soren and Claus. Shortly after that they formed a band call 'Joyspeed'. In their short time as 'Joyspeed', the group release the single "Itzy Bitzy" which showed lackluster success in a one week appearance on Swedish charts before vanishing.

In an attempt to reinvent itself the group dissolved their old contract and secured a new one with the Danish label Universal Music. In September of 1996, they released their debut single "Roses are Red" as Aqua. It stayed on the charts for several weeks and eventually made platinum. It also received a Grammy nomination for the Best Danish Dance Publication. The follow-up single in February of 1997 "My Oh My" also hit a number one spot on the charts.

The precursors of success couldn't have prepared the group for the release of their
Aqua.bioPage2: third single "Barbie Girl" which sold over 4 million copies and lead Aqua to fame world wide. The international success of "Barbie Girl" paved the way for Aqua's first full length album, "Aquarium", release in September of 1997 followed by "Aquarius" in early 2000.

Matt Darey.bioPage1:
Matt Darey leaves quite a trail of names to follow, such as Li Kwan, Tekara, or undoubtedly, Lost Tribe. From midnight raves across the United States to The clubs of Ibiza, his aural melodies can be heard throughout the tangled macabre of trancers the world over... His mixes span across many sets by top DJs, live or otherwise, among those, ATB, Paul Oakenfold, Paul Van Dyk, as well as the awe-inspiring, Binary Finary.

Enter the eternally soothing vocals of Marcella Woods. Marcella has been working very well with Matt for some time. Her words can be heard in many of his songs such as Liberation, a favorite among Massinova Listeners. It is the culmination of intense studio sessions combined with long hours in some of the UK's finest clubs. Liberation has surpassed what has been an illuminating period in both Marcella's and Matt's career. Both artists have a strong following which will carry them into the next generation of trance and assuredly their chemistry, in music and melody, comes an even more exciting future in their careers as well as the world of Electronica.

Apollo Four Forty.bioPage1:
Formed in 1991, Apollo Four Forty has been widely accepted through their unabashed nature to throw a little of everything into the mix. The group got their start with Howard Gray (a former studio engineer), his brother Trevor (trained in classical piano) and longtime friend Noko from their Liverpool school (former guitarist for Howard Devoto's Luxuria).

Influenced initially by the acid-house breakout in the UK the team worked as remixers (often under the name Stealthsonic Orchestra) for the likes of U2, EMF and Shabba Ranks. The final leap into producing their own work began with the single "Astral America" which appeared on the group's own label, Stealth Sonic Records, in 1993. Following their first single the group released "(Don't Fear) The Reaper" and "Krupa" both becoming club hits.

In 1995 the group released their debut album, Millenium Fever, followed by Electro Glide in Blue two years later. They recently resurfaced after a hiatus with the 2000 release of Getting High on Your Own Supply.

Armin van Buuren.bioPage1:
Armin began his career in electronic music at an early age getting his first release at the age of 18. An accomplished DJ, the young producer gained his first UK chart topper "Blue Fear" in the 1999 release on Cyber Records. Eclipsing his previous productions, Armin once again hit the topof the charts with his masterpiece, "Communication" now included on several high-profile collections and mixes.

In the beginning of 1999, he launched his own label, Armind with United Recordings on which he released "One". The second release on that label, "Touch Me" under the name Rising Star was signed to Ministry Of Sound before the records hit the shelves.

His DJ career has also seen growing successes playing venues around the globe after giving up his residency at Nexus (Leiden, Holland). At Nexus he played a 5 hour set every week for three years (1996-1999).

amoebaassassin.bioPage1:
Andy Gray and Steve Sacre began their production endeavors in 1998 with the release of their first single "Rollercoaster". The amoebaassassins gained wide popularity when Paul Oakenfold took notice of the group in early 1998. Having heard their work via a Brian Transeau Radio 1 Essential Mix, Paul quickly worked to license "Rollercoaster" through his Perfecto label. The track became immensely popular in the club scene which led into the "Rollercoaster Tour" around the UK. Following on their success with Perfecto, they produced their follow-up release "Piledriver" along with several remix singles.

Andy and Steve do all of the song writing and lyrics to their productions. Steve adds his vocal talents, giving their songs a characteristic melancholy. Both are also accomplished DJs having played at Cream, Liverpool and Moles, Bath. Undoubtedly their unique style has an will continue to bring them great success in the electonic music scene.

Alice Deejay.bioPage1: Joining the techno-pop scene at the popular Roxy club in Amsterdam, the famed club/dance mixer Alice Deejay introduced her unique spin on the electronic scene. Judy, the woman behind the face of Alice Deejay, performed at several clubs alongside fellow DJ spinsters Josh Wink, DJ Rap, and Paul Oakenfold. Seeking to express the spiritual connection of music and the human mind, Alice Deejay released her debut album, "Who Needs Guitars Anyway?" in March 2000.
